thread.title: Seattle University can’t hold its lead in losing on the road to New Mexico State in volleyball
thread.title_full: Seattle University can’t hold its lead in losing on the road to New Mexico State in volleyball | The Seattle Times

author: Seattle Times staff
title: Seattle University can’t hold its lead in losing on the road to New Mexico State in volleyball
text:
LAS CRUCES, N.M. — Seattle University couldn’t hold on to its edge in the fourth set and dropped a 25-23, 22-25, 14-25, 25-18, 15-13 decision against New Mexico State in volleyball action Saturday.
The Redhawks were up 11-9 in the fourth set, with a 2-1 advantage in sets, when the Aggies rallied with a 12-4 run to take control. New Mexico State (17-5, 7-0 Western Athletic) jumped out to an early lead in the fifth set and SU (12-8, 4-3) couldn’t mount a big enough rally for a comeback.
Martina Samadan topped SU with 19 kills and a .405 hitting percentage, with Matea Mamic collecting 17 kills, six digs, and four blocks and Jelena Vujcin contributing 16 kills, six digs and three service aces.
Andrea Tauai led New Mexico State with 16 kills.

Lexi Biondi had 23 kills and Hannah Lautenbach added 17 kills and 17 digs for SPU.
• Western Washington’s winning streak reached 16 matches as the Vikings (16-2, 10-0 Great Northwest) posted a 25-19, 25-23, 25-20 victory over Alaska Fairbanks (2-15, 2-8). Rachel Roeder led the visiting Vikings with 13 kills on a .435 hitting percentage.
• San Diego (13-6, 7-1 West Coast) scored a 25-18, 21-25, 25-23, 25-11 home victory over Gonzaga (12-9, 3-5). Savannah Blinn had 15 kills for the Zags.
• Central Washington (12-5, 8-2 GNAC) got nine kills from Linden Firethorne in scoring a 25-16, 25-20, 25-23 victory over host Saint Martin’s (2-15, 1-9).
• Northwest University (14-7, 10-5 Cascade) handed Eastern Oregon (19-2, 14-1) its first conference defeat in a 25-22, 21-25, 25-23, 16-25, 15-10 home victory. Amanda Waterman registered a double-double for the Eagles with 14 kills and 10 digs. 
• An eight-match winning streak by Eastern Washington (12-7, 7-1 Big Sky) fell by the wayside as Montana (5-15, 1-7) tallied a 19-25, 25-21, 22-25, 25-16, 20-18 home victory. Ana Jakovljevic had 17 kills for the Eagles.
MEN’S SOCCER • Seattle Pacific (10-1-2, 6-1-2 GNAC) scored twice in the first 3½ minutes on its way to a 4-0 victory over visiting Western Washington (4-6-3, 2-5-2). Mori Tsuchiya opened the scoring at 1:34 and Chaz Jenkins followed at 3:25. Gabe Kellum and Matt Merchant scored second-half goals for SPU.
• Northwest dropped a 3-2 decision to host Carroll to fall to 8-6 (6-3 CCC).
WOMEN’S SOCCER • Caitlyn Jobanek had two goals and Erin Russell one as Western Washington (13-1, 8-0 GNAC) was a 3-1 home winner over Seattle Pacific (9-3-1, 5-3-1). Hannah Huesers scored her 11th goal of the season for the Falcons.
• Sonja Giraud scored the winning goal in the 71st minute, and San Francisco (9-3-3, 3-1 West Coast) held on for a 3-2 victory over host Gonzaga (2-8-5, 1-3-1). Karley Baggerly scored her conference-leading seventh goal for the Zags.
• Mackenzie Nolte scored 34 seconds into overtime to lift visiting Central Washington (4-8, 2-5 GNAC) to a 2-1 victory over Northwest Nazarene (5-6-1, 2-4-1).
• Northwest now is 4-8-2, 3-3-1 in the Cascade Conference after losing 4-1 to host Carroll. 
CROSS COUNTRY • Washington State won the women’s team title at the Division I Pre-Nationals Invitational in Louisville, Ky. The Cougars had 176 points, followed by Buffalo with 183 and Arizona at 203. CharLee Linton led the Cougars with an eighth-place finish in the 6,000-meter Black race in 21:00.1. Devin Bortfeld took 17th in 21:13.6. The WSU men took 13th with Michael Williams at 36th in 23:49.7 for the 8,000-meter course. For Eastern Washington, Sarah Reiter was 16th out of the 311 runners and EWU took 13th among the 46 teams.
• Gonzaga took first place among both the men and the women at the Inland Empire Challenge in Lewiston, Idaho. Among the men, the Zags scored 17 points while Eastern Washington had 59 for second in the four-team field. Troy Fraley was the top Zag individually with a fourth-place finish in 24:17 for the 8,000 meters. Among the women, the Zags won with 21 points with Montana second at 34. Shelby Mills took third for the Zags in 16:56 for 6,000 meters.
From sports-information reports.
